[[File:Bench Aus.jpg|thumb|300px|right|A judge's '''bench''' in a [[courtroom]] in [[Beechworth, Victoria]], [[Australia]]. The term "bench" is also used as a [[metonymy|metonym]] to mean all the [[judge]]s of a certain [[court]] or members of a [[judiciary]].]] [[File:The Grand Bench of the Japanese Supreme Court.jpg|thumb|300px|right|The [[Supreme Court of Japan]] Grand Bench seats 15 justices.]]
'''Bench''' in [[law|legal]] contexts means simply the location in a [[courtroom]] where a [[judge]] sits. The historical roots of that meaning come from judges formerly having sat on long seats or [[Bench (furniture)|benches]] (freestanding or against a wall) when presiding over a [[court]].<ref name=Walker>{{Cite book | last = Walker | first = David | author-link = | last2 = | first2 = | author2-link = | title = Oxford Companion to Law | place = | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | year = 1980 | volume = | edition = | page = 123 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=4GgYAAAAIAAJ | doi = | id = | isbn =0-19-866110-X }}</ref> The bench is usually an elevated desk area that allows a judge to view the entire courtroom.
The word also has a broader meaning in the [[law]]&nbsp;– the term "[[Bench (metonymy)|bench]]" is a [[metonymy|metonym]] used to describe members of the [[judiciary]] collectively,<ref>In [[Italy]], in the law on the conflict between powers, the ordinance drawn by the judge at the bench (...) is the legal system's response to the suffered invasion of his range of power: {{cite journal|last1=Buonomo|first1=Giampiero|title = La Consulta apre alla libertà delle forme e ascolta i giudici che sostituiscono l'ordinanza al ricorso|journal= Diritto&Giustizia edizione online |date=2005| url= https://www.questia.com/projects#!/project/89394844}} {{Subscription required |via=[[Questia]]}}</ref> or the judges of a particular court, such as the [[Queen's Bench]] or the [[Common Bench]] in [[England and Wales]], or the [[United States federal courts|federal]] bench in the [[United States]].<ref name=Walker/> The term is also used when all the judges of a certain court sit together to decide a [[legal case|case]], as in the phrase "before the full bench" (also called "[[en banc]]").<ref>{{cite book | last = Black | first = Henry Campbell | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = [[Black's Law Dictionary]], 6th ed. | publisher = [[West Publishing]] | year = 1990 | location = St. Paul, MN. | pages = 155 | url = | doi = | id = | isbn =0-314-76271-X }}</ref>
The bench was a typical feature of the courts of the [[Order of St. John]] in [[Malta]], such as at the [[Castellania (Valletta)|Castellania]], where judges and the nominated College of Advocates sat for court cases and review laws.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Scietia|last=Harding|first=Hugh W.|date=1950|title=Advocates Under the Code de Rohan and the Present Law|url=http://melitensiawth.com/incoming/Index/Scientia%20(Malta)/Scientia.%2016(1950)3(Jul.-Sept.)/02.pdf|volume=3|issue=2|page=121|issn=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170520111517/http://melitensiawth.com/incoming/Index/Scientia%20%28Malta%29/Scientia.%2016%281950%293%28Jul.-Sept.%29/02.pdf|archive-date=20 May 2017|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref>
The term is used to differentiate judges ("the bench") from [[Lawyer|attorneys]] or [[barristers]] ("[[Bar (law)|the bar]]"). The phrase "bench and bar" denotes all judges and lawyers collectively.<ref name=Walker/>
