'''Prolok''' was a pioneering copy protection system developed by W. Krag Brotby and [[Vault Corporation]] in 1982. Prolok was involved in the [[Copyright law of the United States|copyright law]] case [[Vault Corp. v. Quaid Software Ltd.]] which allowed software to be used in certain situations that the copyright holder did not originally intend.
Prolok was developed for [[Apple II]], [[CP/M]], [[CP/M-86]], [[MS-DOS]], [[Microsoft Windows]] and [[OS/2]]. US Patent 4,785,361 <ref name="google">{{cite web|url=http://www.google.com/patents/US4785361|title=Patent US4785361 - Method and apparatus for frustrating the unauthorized copying of recorded data - Google Patents|publisher=google.com|accessdate=2015-12-24}}</ref>
