In [[property law]] of the United States and some Canadian provinces, '''pur autre vie''' ([[Old French language|Old French]] for "for another['s] life") is a duration of a property interest.<ref name="wex">{{cite web|title=Life estate pur autre vie|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/wex/life_estate_pur_autre_vie|website=Wex|publisher=Cornell Law School|accessdate=23 May 2017}}</ref><ref name="sutton">{{cite web|url=http://www.sutton.com/dictionary/life+estate+pur+autre+vie|title=life estate pur autre vie|publisher=Sutton Group Realty Services Ltd.|accessdate=2011-03-26|work=Sutton Real Estate Dictionary}}</ref>  While it is similar to a [[life estate]], it differs in that a person's life interest will last for the life of ''another person'' instead of their own.<ref name="wex"/><ref name="sutton"/><ref>''See'' [[Future Interest]].</ref>  For example, if Bob is given use of the family house for as long as his mother lives, he has possession of the house pur autre vie.  Pur autre vie can occur when a [[Remainder (law)#Contingent_remainder|contingent remainder]] is destroyed, in a [[Merger doctrine (property law)|Doctrine of Merger]] situation, where one person acquires the life estate of another and thereby destroys a remainder not already vested.<ref>''See'' [[Merger doctrine (property law)|Doctrine of Merger]].</ref>

